    "We illustrate how this works for grouptheoretical fusion categories where the module categories have been classified [68,[96][97][98] and provide the physical picture in terms of topological interfaces and their fusion.We first recall that group-theoretical fusion categories are usually denoted as C(G, ω, H, ψ) where the defining data consists of a finite group G, its group 3-cocycle ω ∈ H 3 (G, U(1)), a subgroup H ⊂ G, and a 2-cochain ψ ∈ C 2 (H, U(1)), subject to the condition that dψ = ω| H. The special case C(G, ω, 1, 1) is the group category Vec ω G with a 't Hooft anomaly captured by the 3-cocycle ω."
